ISSUE #3 — Multiple Initializations / Stacking Intervals
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Line:       216 (startHeartbeat), 228 (startObserver), 283 (init)
Severity:   HIGH
Code:       _heartbeat = setInterval(function() { ... }, HEARTBEAT_MS);

Detail:     If this IIFE is loaded more than once (common with tag managers,
            SPA re-renders, or script re-injection), there is no guard against
            creating duplicate heartbeat intervals and mutation observers.
            Each duplicate consumes resources and causes redundant DOM
            operations. The `_heartbeat` check only works within the same
            closure instance.

Solution:   Use a global sentinel to prevent double-initialization:

            if (window.__igCabInjectorActive) return;
            window.__igCabInjectorActive = true;

            And clear it in the destroy function:
            window.__igCabInjectorActive = false;

================================================================================

ISSUE #4 — Overly Broad MutationObserver (Performance)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Line:       239-242
Severity:   HIGH
Code:       _observer.observe(document.body || document.documentElement, {
                childList: true,
                subtree: true
            });

Detail:     Observing the entire document subtree fires the callback on EVERY
            DOM mutation anywhere on the page. On a complex SPA this can fire
            hundreds of times per second (scrolls triggering lazy-load,
            analytics, ads). Each firing calls mount() which runs multiple
            querySelector calls — causing layout thrashing and jank.

Solution:   1. Narrow the observe target to a known ancestor of the container.
            2. Debounce the observer callback (like the resize handler).
            3. Disconnect the observer once mounted:

            _observer = new MutationObserver(function() {
                if (!_mounted && mount()) {
                    _observer.disconnect();
                    _observer = null;
                }
            });

================================================================================

ISSUE #5 — Global Namespace Pollution
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Line:       258
Severity:   MEDIUM-HIGH
Code:       window.__igCabInjectorDestroy = function() { ... };

Detail:     Exposing the destroy function on the global window object risks
            name collisions with other scripts and allows any third-party
            script on the page to call destroy — potentially used as a
            denial-of-service against the UI component or to manipulate page
            state.

Solution:   Use a namespaced object or dispatch a CustomEvent pattern:

            window.IndiGo = window.IndiGo || {};
            window.IndiGo.cabInjector = { destroy: function() { ... } };

            Or use a CustomEvent listener so external code cannot directly
            invoke internal functions:

            window.addEventListener('ig-cab-injector-destroy', function() { ... });

